<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n22041h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n22" href="#n22041h">N22 (VI.B.17)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n22all.htm#n22041h"> 41(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> caudle brought</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;the cry of the maidenhead&ldquo;: A singular custom which obliged the bride to utter a loud cry when she lost her virginity, and to which the groomsmen replied by bringing a large bowl of caudle or some invigorating drink into the bed chamber. From some verses written by Clement Marot on the marriage of the Duke of Ferrara to Princess R&eacute;n&eacute;e, it would appear that the custom existed at the Court of France. <small> Robert B. Douglas, trans., <a name="RBDM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBDM"><cite title="source">ONE HUNDRED MERRIE AND DELIGHTSOME STORIES</cite></a> (1923) Story 30</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
